				<div class="comment-text">
					<p>Okay, I am biased in really focusing on the bits of the long tracks that are addressed to me, but I am amused to see that she applies lots of vitriol and insults to my comments even after you say:<br />
&#8220;I‚Äôm also happy to have more research done on the safety of vaccines‚Äìand once again, it‚Äôs being done. Not by accupuncturists ‚Äújust asking questions,‚Äù of course, but by real doctors and PhDs who are asking questions in order to learn more about the problem, rather than as a rhetorical tactic.&#8221;</p>
<p>Awesome.</p>
<p>&#8220;I think the fact that you posted it without bothering to think about it says quite a lot about your methodology: attack first, think later. Never admit error.&#8221;</p>
<p>Again, awesome.  She has blamed me for committing many errors, but has not explained what they are.</p>
<p>&#8220;Not by accupuncturists ‚Äújust asking questions,‚Äù of course, but by real doctors and PhDs who are asking questions in order to learn more about the problem, rather than as a rhetorical tactic&#8221;</p>
<p>Hey!  I want her to go through the procedure.  She is not satisfied by the several epidemiological and matched case studies, so she need to design her own study that does not violate the Belmont Report.  Or at least explain clearly why the ones done on several continents that included the medical records of millions of children are not sufficient.  Complaining that a study of antigen load over two the first two year vaccine schedule that &#8220;only&#8221; compared ASD kids matched with non-ASD kids was not adequate because it was not a vax vs. unvax study is a lame and quite inadequate criticism.</p>
<p>&#8220;Use your ‚Äúsearch thingy‚Äù to look up the results of studies on chelation for children suffering from legitimate heavy metal toxicity. Removing the metals didn‚Äôt repair their neurological injuries. They didn‚Äôt show significant improvements.&#8221;</p>
<p>Ah, very true.  I used those studies trying to tell the &#8220;Mercury Militia&#8221; moms advocating chelation that it was a bad idea. One reason I dropped from that email listserv was that one of those was an employee of a doctor who was providing those services trying to drum up business, a doctor that one of the Special Masters of the Omnibus Autism Vaccine cases severely criticized, see  <a href="http://www.uscfc.uscourts.gov/sites/default/files/vaccine_files/Vowell.Snyder.pdf" rel="nofollow">http://www.uscfc.uscourts.gov/sites/default/files/vaccine_files/Vowell.Snyder.pdf</a>:</p>
<p>&lt;</p>
<p>blockquote&gt;To conclude that Colten‚Äôs condition was the result of his MMR vaccine, an objective observer would have to emulate Lewis Carroll‚Äôs White Queen and be able to believe six impossible (or, at least, highly improbable) things before breakfast. The families of children with ASD and the court have waited in vain for adequate evidence to support the autism-MMR hypothesis. Although I have the deepest sympathy for families like Colten‚Äôs, struggling emotionally and financially to find answers about ASD‚Äôs causes, and reliable therapies to treat ASD‚Äôs symptoms, I must decide Colten‚Äôs case based on the evidence before me</p>
<p>&#8220;The results have been studied. Vaccines don‚Äôt cause autism, even with the aluminum.&#8221;</p>
<p>Um, yeah.  You can&#8217;t really pinpoint that a particular ingredient causes harm, when the actual end product really does not show harm, especially when compared to the disease it is supposed to prevent!</p>
<p>&#8220;We‚Äìand I include you‚Äìcan only speculate. Having spent the last two years studying irrationality.&#8221;</p>
<p>I have spent more than twenty years dealing with irrationality.  From explaining that the kid&#8217;s seizures just happened, that his lack of speech was not from the lack of me speaking to him (in two languages!), or that just because he communicated in sign language does not mean he is deaf or stupid. Le sigh.  And his last seizures were from an actual disease, so it was not a vaccine!</p>
<p>Thank you, Colin, for joining the endeavor for healthy rationality.</p>
